    <div class="alpheios-lex-entry" lemma-id="n4026" body-key="α">
          <b><span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἐύς, ἐύ</span></b> , and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἠύς, ἠύ</span>, gen. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἑῆος</span>, acc. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἐύν, ἠύν</span>, pl.
          gen. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἑά̄ων</span>: synonym of <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἀγαθός</span> and <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">καλός</span>, the neut. forms of the sing. mostly adverbial, see
            <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">εὖ. ἐὺς παῖς, υἱός, θεραπών, Βίᾱς, παιδὸς
            ἑῆος</span>, esp. in Il.; also <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">μένος
            ἠύ</span>, ‘noble ardor,’ <i><span class="en">Od.
            2.271</span></i>, etc.; <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἠύς τε μέγας τε</span>,
            <i><span class="en">Il. 2.653</span></i>.— gen. pl. <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">ἑά̄ων</span>, <span class="alpheios-lex-gloss">of good things,
            blessings</span>, <i><span class="en">Il. 24.528</span></i>
          <span class="alpheios-lex-greek" lang="grc">; θεοὶ δωτῆρες ἑά̄ων</span>, <i><span class="en">Od. 8.325</span></i>.</div> <div class="alpheios-lex-footnotes en"> </div>
